like the native image failed because log4j wasn’t included. Instead, it referenced the JUL path. At runtime, LogManager can’t find java.home, which may be why log4j is absent—possibly the testRuntimeOnly dependency wasn’t included in the native image. I wonder if I should set the System property `hsqldb.reconfig_logging=false`, but that could disable log4j. Since the log4j class isn’t reachable, I might need to generate metadata for it, but that seems tricky!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Reviewing logging configurations**\\n\\nI need to ensure tests run under native by default. If log4j isn’t available in the native image due to missing metadata, the static initialization of FrameworkLogger could fail unless I set `hsqldb.reconfig_logging=false`. But then I’d avoid that failure without achieving coverage. For the JVM, the property only matters if log4j is available. I should set the property before the first FrameworkLogger access, ensuring JVM uses the log4j path but checking how native handles it without log4j metadata. It’s a bit complicated!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Ensuring log4j coverage in native**\\n\\nI’m realizing that there might be no active coverage in native if it fails before log4j is considered. But, the dynamic report probably includes native. If that’s the case, I need to make sure the native image includes log4j. I should use `testImplementation` instead of `testRuntimeOnly` and import `Level/LogManager`. By adding direct typed references to log4j classes in the test, I can ensure that they get included in the native image. It's a little convoluted, but it should work!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_nqyykvrk4okW64FmnXYJyRJN|fc_0b6c3f5bbde7d4f2016a116295f6f08194924e40abfa3b23f1", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.hsqldb/hsqldb/2.4.1/build.gradle", "edits": [{"oldText": "    testImplementation \"org.hsqldb:hsqldb:$libraryVersion\"\n    testImplementation 'org.assertj:assertj-core:3.22.0'\n